  <data name="TheoryStaffTitle" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Meet the staff</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryStaffSummary" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Music notes live on five lines and four spaces.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryStaffBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The staff is the ladder for written music. Notes can sit on a line or in a space. When a note is too low or too high, we add small ledger lines so the ladder can keep going.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryTrebleClefTitle" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Meet the treble clef</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryTrebleClefSummary" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The treble clef tells us these notes are the higher notes.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryTrebleClefBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The treble clef is also called the G clef. Its curl points to the G line, so that line is sol, or G4. From there the note names climb step by step.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryTrebleClefCallout" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The highlighted note is sol, also called G4.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryNoteMapTitle" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Notes from low do to high ti</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryNoteMapSummary" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Read the notes like stair steps from low to high.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryNoteMapBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>This first range starts under the staff at low do and climbs to high ti above the staff. Each next line or space moves one step: do, re, mi, fa, sol, la, ti, then do again.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryNoteMapCallout" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Follow the notes from left to right: every note is one step higher.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheorySingleNoteTitle" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Meet {0}</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheorySingleNoteSummary" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>{0} is also written as {1}.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheorySingleNoteBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>This page shows {0}. Look at whether the note sits on a line or in a space, and notice if it needs a ledger line.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheorySingleNoteCallout" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>This note is {0}, also called {1}.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryAccidentalsTitle" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Meet sharps and flats</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryAccidentalsSummary" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>A sharp raises a note. A flat lowers a note.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryAccidentalsBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Sharps and flats are accidentals. A sharp moves the note one tiny step higher, and a flat moves it one tiny step lower. The note stays on the same line or space, but the accidental tells you which nearby key to play.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryBlackKeysTitle" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Black keys have two names</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryBlackKeysSummary" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The same black key can be named as a sharp or a flat.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryBlackKeysBody" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Look at the black keys between the white keys. The black key above do is do sharp, but it is also re flat. Both names point to the same sound, so either name can be correct depending on the music.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="TheoryBlackKeysCallout" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Each black key shows its sharp name and its flat name.</value>
  </data>
